# Naming Conventions

## React Hooks (Client)

### Hook Naming Patterns

**Queries (reads)** - Mirror backend API names:

- Single items: `useItem(id)`, `useItemBySlug(slug)`
- Lists: `useItems(options?)`, `useItemsByCategory(categoryId)`
- Lists with relations: `useItemsWithAuthors()`
- Boolean checks: `useIsItemFavorited(itemId)`
- Special queries: `useFeaturedItems()`, `useItemsCount()`

**Mutations (writes)** - Use verb prefix + entity:

```ts
// Mutations - Use appropriate semantic verb
export function useArchiveItem(); // Soft delete (set status to 'archived')
export function useCreateItem(); // Create new
export function useDestroyItem(); // Hard delete (permanent removal from DB)
export function useRemoveItem(); // Remove from association/list (non-destructive)
export function useUpdateItem(); // Update existing
export function useUpdateItemStatus(); // Update specific status field
export function useAddFavoriteItem(); // Add to favorites (join table operation)
export function useRemoveFavoriteItem(); // Remove from favorites (join table operation)
```

### Naming Principles

- Drop redundant prefixes when file/feature provides context
- Use singular for single items, plural for arrays
- Mirror backend API conventions for consistency
- Use `useCurrent*` pattern for authenticated/context-based data

### Query Hook Return Pattern

All query hooks return a consistent object shape for familiarity and destructuring:

```ts
// Single item hook
export function useItem(id: string) {
  const data = useQuery(api.items.get, { id });

  return {
    data,
    isLoading: data === undefined,
    notFound: data === null,
  };
}

// Usage - familiar destructuring pattern
const { data: item, isLoading, notFound } = useItem(id);
if (isLoading) return <Loading />;
if (notFound) return <NotFound />;
return <div>{item.title}</div>;
```

**Benefits:**

- Familiar to React Query users
- Consistent shape across all hooks
- Easy to destructure with renaming
- Explicit `isLoading` and `notFound` states

**Pattern for different return types:**

```ts
// Returns single item or null
export function useItem(id: string) {
  const data = useQuery(api.items.get, { id });
  return {
    data,
    isLoading: data === undefined,
    notFound: data === null,
  };
}

// Returns array (never null)
export function useItems(limit?: number) {
  const data = useQuery(api.items.list, { limit });
  return {
    data: data ?? [],
    isLoading: data === undefined,
  };
}

// Returns boolean
export function useIsItemFavorited(itemId: string) {
  const data = useQuery(api.users.isItemFavorited, { itemId });
  return {
    data: data ?? false,
    isLoading: data === undefined,
  };
}

// Returns number
export function useItemsCount() {
  const data = useQuery(api.items.getCount);
  return {
    data: data ?? 0,
    isLoading: data === undefined,
  };
}
```

### Mutation Hook Patterns

**Simple mutations** - Direct pass-through when no error handling needed:

```ts
export function useCreateItem() {
  return useMutation(api.items.create);
}

// Usage
const createItem = useCreateItem();
await createItem({ title: 'New Item' });
```

**With error handling** - Use `useMutationWithErrorHandling` for automatic error reporting:

```ts
import { useMutationWithErrorHandling } from '@/lib/services/errors';

// In component
const { mutate, isLoading, error } = useMutationWithErrorHandling(api.items.create, {
  onSuccess: () => router.push('/items'),
});
```

Reference: See `error-handling.mdc` for complete mutation error handling patterns.

### Composite Hooks

Combine multiple queries for page-level patterns to reduce boilerplate:

```ts
// Composite hook for item detail pages
export function useItemDetailPage(id: string) {
  const { data: item, isLoading } = useItem(id);
  const { data: relatedItems } = useItems(
    item ? { categoryId: item.categoryId, limit: 3 } : 'skip',
  );

  return {
    data: item,
    isLoading,
    notFound: item === null,
    relatedItems,
  };
}

// Usage - all data in one call
const { data, isLoading, notFound, relatedItems } = useItemDetailPage(id);
```

**When to combine:**

- Specific page/component always needs queries together
- Want unified loading state across related queries
- Have dependent queries (one feeds into another)

**When to keep separate:**

- Queries used in different combinations across app
- Need maximum flexibility and reusability
- Want optimal React performance (granular re-renders)

### Loading States

Per Convex best practices, check for `undefined` internally to determine loading state. Hooks wrap
this check into an explicit `isLoading` property to provide a familiar React Query-style API.

```ts
// Hook implementation
export function useItem(id: string) {
  const data = useQuery(api.items.get, { id });
  return {
    data,
    isLoading: data === undefined, // undefined = still loading
    notFound: data === null, // null = not found
  };
}

// Component usage
const { data, isLoading, notFound } = useItem(id);
```

Reference:
[Convex UI Patterns](https://docs.convex.dev/understanding/best-practices/other-recommendations#ui-patterns)

## Feature Queries (Server)

Use the `get`/`list` pattern to indicate return type:

```ts
// queries.ts - Server reads

// Single items (return one or null)
export async function getItem(id);
export async function getItemBySlug(slug);

// Arrays (return array)
export async function getItems({ filters });
export async function getItemsByCategory(categoryId);
```

**Pattern:**

- **`get*`** - Returns single item or null
- **`list*`** - Returns arrays

## Feature Actions (Server)

Use clear verb prefixes to indicate the operation:

```ts
// actions.ts - Server writes
export async function archiveItem(id); // Soft delete (set status to 'archived')
export async function createItem(data); // Create new
export async function destroyItem(id); // Hard delete (permanent removal from DB)
export async function publishItem(id); // Specific status action
export async function removeItem(id); // Remove from association/list (non-destructive)
export async function updateItem(id, data); // Update existing
```

## Service Functions

### Auth Service

```ts
// client.ts
export function signIn(credentials);
export function signOut();
export function useSession();

// server.ts
export async function getServerSession();
export async function requireAuth();
```

### Email Service

```ts
// server.ts
export async function sendEmail(to, subject, body);
export async function sendResetPasswordEmail(user);
export async function sendWelcomeEmail(user);
```

### Analytics Service

```ts
// client.ts
export function trackEvent(name, properties);
export function trackPageView(path);

// server.ts
export async function trackServerEvent(name, properties);
```

## Utility Functions

Use clear, descriptive names:

```ts
// date.ts
export function formatDate(date);
export function formatRelativeTime(date);

// string.ts
export function capitalize(str);
export function slugify(str);

// array.ts
export function groupBy<T>(arr, key);
export function unique<T>(arr);
```

## Type Naming

```ts
// types.ts
export type CreateItemInput = {...}
export type Item = {...}
export type ItemWithRelations = {...}
export type UpdateItemInput = {...}

// ✅ Good
export type ItemCardProps = {...}
export type ItemData = {...}

// ❌ Bad. Avoid generic names
export type Data = {...}
export type Props = {...}
```

## Constants

Use `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for true constants:

```ts
// constants.ts
export const API_BASE_URL = 'https://api.example.com';
export const DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE = 20;
export const MAX_ITEMS_PER_USER = 100;
```

Use `camelCase` for configuration objects:

```ts
// config.ts
export const authConfig = {
  providers: [...],
  session: {...},
};
```

